text: Many people have tested positive for antibodies without ever getting COVID-19. But this doesn’t mean they’re immune to the virus, writes @JamesHamblin: https://t.co/g66O9d5HVR

name: TheAtlantic
text: "No American figure has wrestled with the contest between idealism and realism as publicly as Barack Obama. His new memoir, 'A Promised Land,' can be read as a long dialogue between these opposing visions," @nytdavidbrooks writes. https://t.co/lX90F3y0NX

name: TheAtlantic
text: Mexico's president hasn't recognized Joe Biden as America's president-elect. But AMLO is offering a lesson about when to concede elections, @realcpaz reports: https://t.co/6jNOnjp4CV

name: TheAtlantic
text: "Some on the Biden team, veterans of the Obama administration, will be tempted to restart relationships and reboot old plans as if nothing has happened. That would be a mistake," @anneapplebaum writes: https://t.co/jb84HoRxq0

name: TheAtlantic
text: Pfizer and Moderna’s vaccines both target the coronavirus' spike protein, as do many vaccine candidates still in development. These initial successes suggest that several more COVID-19 vaccines may soon cross the finish line, @sarahzhang writes: https://t.co/YA1CqfVL55

text: By supporting Trump’s baseless narrative that he won the election, Republicans could hamstring Joe Biden's ability to lead. But they're hurting themselves in the process, writes @RonBrownstein. https://t.co/MIWSUMjVRF

text: "Evidence from around the world—and even from New York City—shows not only that many schools should remain open, but that officials should take more steps to open up classrooms," @nschwalbe writes: https://t.co/nfTEZySWvb

name: TheAtlantic
text: Many Americans are under the impression that no matter how high cases surge in the coming weeks, deaths will not reach the heights of the spring. The truth is more grim, write @alexismadrigal and @whet. https://t.co/2cXplY2zc9
